# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: scada-historian
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:scada-historian/data-historian] In manufacturing, an **operational historian** is a time-series database application that is developed for operational process data.
[src:scada-historian/data-historian] Historian software is often embedded or used in conjunction with standard DCS and PLC control systems to provide enhanced data capture, validation, compression, and aggregation capabilities.
[src:scada-historian/data-historian] Historians have been deployed in almost every industry and contribute to functions such as supervisory control, performance monitoring, quality assurance, and, more recently, machine learning applications which can learn from vast quantities of historical data.
[src:scada-historian/data-historian] These systems were originally developed to capture instrumentation and control data, which led many to use the term "tag" for a stream of process data, referring to the physical "tags" which had been placed on instrumentation for manually capturing data.
[src:scada-historian/data-historian] Raw data may be accessed via OPC HDA, SQL, or REST API interfaces.
[src:scada-historian/data-historian] Operational historians are typically used within the manufacturing facility by engineers and operators for supervisory functions and analysis.
[src:scada-historian/data-historian] An operational historian will typically capture all instrumentation and control data, whereas an enterprise historian that is deployed to support business functions will capture only a subset of the plant data.
[src:scada-historian/data-historian] Typically, these applications offer data access through dedicated APIs (Application Programming Interfaces) and SDKs (Software Development Kits) which offer high-performance read and write operations.
[src:scada-historian/data-historian] These operate through vendor-specific or custom applications.
[src:scada-historian/data-historian] Front-end tools for trending process data over time are the most common interfaces to these databases.
[src:scada-historian/data-historian] As opposed to enterprise historians, the data access layer in the operational historian is designed to offer sophisticated data fetching modes without complex information analysis facilities.
[src:scada-historian/data-historian] Even though the operational historians are rarely relational database management systems, they often offer SQL-based interfaces to query the database.
[src:scada-historian/data-historian] In most of such implementations, the dialect does not follow the SQL standard in order to provide syntax for specifying data access operations parameters.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] MES creates the "as-built" record, capturing the data, processes and outcomes of the manufacturing process.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] This can be especially important in regulated industries, such as food and beverage or pharmaceutical, where documentation and proof of processes, events and actions may be required.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] As of 2025, the manufacturing execution systems are shifting from rigid, monolithic on-premise software to modular, cloud-connected platforms.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] "Manufacturing execution systems [help] create flawless manufacturing processes and provide real-time feedback of requirement changes", and provide information at a single source.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] A wide variety of systems arose using collected data for a dedicated purpose.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] Further development of these systems during the 1990s introduced overlap in functionality.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] Then the Manufacturing Enterprise Solutions Association International (MESA) introduced some structure by defining 11 functions that set the scope of MES.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] In 2000, the ANSI/ISA-95 standard merged this model with the Purdue Reference Model (PRM).
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] A functional hierarchy was defined in which MES were situated at Level 3 between ERP at Level 4 and process control at Levels 0, 1, 2.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] With the publication of the third part of the standard in 2005, activities in Level 3 were divided over four main operations: production, quality, logistics and maintenance.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] Between 2005 and 2013, additional or revised parts of the ANSI/ISA-95 standard defined the architecture of an MES into more detail, covering how to internally distribute functionality and what information to exchange internally as well as externally.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] Over the years, international standards and models have refined the scope of such systems in terms of activities.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] MES integrates with ISA-95 (previous Purdue Reference Model, “95”) with multiple relationships.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] The collection of systems acting on the ISA-95 Level 3 can be called manufacturing operations management systems (MOMS).
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] Apart from an MES, there are typically laboratory information management system (LIMS), warehouse management system (WMS) and computerized maintenance management system (CMMS).
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] Examples of systems acting on ISA-95 Level 4 are product lifecycle management (PLM), enterprise resource planning (ERP), customer relationship management (CRM), human resource management (HRM), and process development execution system (PDES).
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] In many cases, middleware enterprise application integration (EAI) systems are being used to exchange transaction messages between MES and Level 4 systems.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] A common data definition, B2MML, has been defined within the ISA-95 standard to link MES systems to these Level 4 systems.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] Systems acting on ISA-95 Level 2 are supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA), programmable logic controllers (PLC), distributed control systems (DCS) and building automation systems (BAS).
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] Most MES systems include connectivity as part of their product offering.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] Direct communication of plant floor equipment data is established by connecting to the PLC.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] Often, plant floor data is first collected and diagnosed for real-time control in a DCS or SCADA system.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] In this case, the MES systems connect to these Level 2 systems for exchanging plant floor data.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] The industry standard for plant floor connectivity has evolved from OLE for Process Control (OPC) to OPC Unified Architecture (OPC-UA).
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] Unlike its predecessor, OPC-UA is platform-independent, allowing it to run on Linux and embedded devices while offering robust security models.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] In modern Industry 4.0 architectures, MES connectivity often extends beyond the traditional hierarchy.
[src:scada-historian/manufacturing-execution-system] Systems increasingly utilize IIoT protocols like MQTT (often with Sparkplug B) to transmit lightweight data to cloud-based analytics platforms, creating a hybrid architecture where OPC-UA handles complex machine data and MQTT handles rapid telemetry.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] In IPC, control theory provides the theoretical framework to understand system dynamics, predict outcomes and design control strategies to ensure predetermined objectives, utilizing concepts like feedback loops, stability analysis and controller design.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] On the other hand, the physical apparatus of IPC, based on automation technologies, consists of several components.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Firstly, a network of sensors continuously measure various process variables (such as temperature, pressure, etc.) and product quality variables.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] This creates a continuous closed-loop cycle of measurement, comparison, control action, and re-evaluation which guarantees that the process remains within established parameters.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] The HMI (Human-Machine Interface) acts as the "control panel" for the IPC system where small number of human operators can monitor the process and make informed decisions regarding adjustments.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] IPCs can range from controlling the temperature and level of a single process vessel (controlled environment tank for mixing, separating, reacting, or storing materials in industrial processes.) to a complete chemical processing plant with several thousand control feedback loops.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] IPC provides several critical benefits to manufacturing companies.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] By maintaining a tight control over key process variables, it helps reduce energy use, minimize waste and shorten downtime for peak efficiency and reduced costs.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] It ensures consistent and improved product quality with little variability, which satisfies the customers and strengthens the company's reputation.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] It improves safety by detecting and alerting human operators about potential issues early, thus preventing accidents, equipment failures, process disruptions and costly downtime.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Analyzing trends and behaviors in the vast amounts of data collected real-time helps engineers identify areas of improvement, refine control strategies and continuously enhance production efficiency using a data-driven approach.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] IPC is used across a wide range of industries where precise control is important.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] The applications can range from controlling the temperature and level of a single process vessel, to a complete chemical processing plant with several thousand control loops.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] In automotive manufacturing, IPC ensures consistent quality by meticulously controlling processes like welding and painting.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Mining operations are optimized with IPC monitoring ore crushing and adjusting conveyor belt speeds for maximum output.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Dredging benefits from precise control of suction pressure, dredging depth and sediment discharge rate by IPC, ensuring efficient and sustainable practices.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Pulp and paper production leverages IPC to regulate chemical processes (e.g., pH and bleach concentration) and automate paper machine operations to control paper sheet moisture content and drying temperature for consistent quality.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] In chemical plants, it ensures the safe and efficient production of chemicals by controlling temperature, pressure and reaction rates.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Oil refineries use it to smoothly convert crude oil into gasoline and other petroleum products.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] In power plants, it helps maintain stable operating conditions necessary for a continuous electricity supply.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] In food and beverage production, it helps ensure consistent texture, safety and quality.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Pharmaceutical companies relies on it to produce life-saving drugs safely and effectively.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] The development of large industrial process control systems has been instrumental in enabling the design of large high volume and complex processes, which could not be otherwise economically or safely operated.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Early process control breakthroughs came most frequently in the form of water control devices.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Ktesibios of Alexandria is credited for inventing float valves to regulate water level of water clocks in the 3rd century BC.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] In the 1st century AD, Heron of Alexandria invented a water valve similar to the fill valve used in modern toilets.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Later process controls inventions involved basic physics principles.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] In 1620, Cornelis Drebbel invented a bimetallic thermostat for controlling the temperature in a furnace.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] In 1681, Denis Papin discovered the pressure inside a vessel could be regulated by placing weights on top of the vessel lid.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] In 1745, Edmund Lee created the fantail to improve windmill efficiency; a fantail was a smaller windmill placed 90° of the larger fans to keep the face of the windmill pointed directly into the oncoming wind.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] With the dawn of the Industrial Revolution in the 1760s, process controls inventions were aimed to replace human operators with mechanized processes.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] In 1784, Oliver Evans created a water-powered flourmill which operated using buckets and screw conveyors.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Henry Ford applied the same theory in 1910 when the assembly line was created to decrease human intervention in the automobile production process.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] For continuously variable process control it was not until 1922 that a formal control law for what we now call PID control or three-term control was first developed using theoretical analysis, by Russian American engineer Nicolas Minorsky.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Minorsky was researching and designing automatic ship steering for the US Navy and based his analysis on observations of a helmsman.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] He noted the helmsman steered the ship based not only on the current course error, but also on past error, as well as the current rate of change; this was then given a mathematical treatment by Minorsky.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] His goal was stability, not general control, which simplified the problem significantly.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] While proportional control provided stability against small disturbances, it was insufficient for dealing with a steady disturbance, notably a stiff gale (due to steady-state error), which required adding the integral term.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Finally, the derivative term was added to improve stability and control.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Process control of large industrial plants has evolved through many stages.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Initially, control would be from panels local to the process plant.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] However this required a large manpower resource to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] The next logical development was the transmission of all plant measurements to a permanently-staffed central control room.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Effectively this was the centralization of all the localized panels, with the advantages of lower manning levels and easier overview of the process.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Often the controllers were behind the control room panels, and all automatic and manual control outputs were transmitted back to plant.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] However, whilst providing a central control focus, this arrangement was inflexible as each control loop had its own controller hardware, and continual operator movement within the control room was required to view different parts of the process.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] With the coming of electronic processors and graphic displays it became possible to replace these discrete controllers with computer-based algorithms, hosted on a network of input/output racks with their own control processors.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] These could be distributed around the plant, and communicate with the graphic display in the control room or rooms.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] The distributed control system (DCS) was born.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] The introduction of DCSs allowed easy interconnection and re-configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and easy interfacing with other production computer systems.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] The accompanying diagram is a general model which shows functional manufacturing levels in a large process using processor and computer-based control.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] To determine the fundamental model for any process, the inputs and outputs of the system are defined differently than for other chemical processes.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] The balance equations are defined by the control inputs and outputs rather than the material inputs.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] The control model is a set of equations used to predict the behavior of a system and can help determine what the response to change will be.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] The state variable (x) is a measurable variable that is a good indicator of the state of the system, such as temperature (energy balance), volume (mass balance) or concentration (component balance).
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Input variable (u) is a specified variable that commonly include flow rates.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] The entering and exiting flows are both considered control inputs.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] The control input can be classified as a manipulated, disturbance, or unmonitored variable.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Parameters (p) are usually a physical limitation and something that is fixed for the system, such as the vessel volume or the viscosity of the material.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Output (y) is the metric used to determine the behavior of the system.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] The control output can be classified as measured, unmeasured, or unmonitored.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Processes can be characterized as batch, continuous, or hybrid.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Batch applications require that specific quantities of raw materials be combined in specific ways for particular duration to produce an intermediate or end result.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] One example is the production of adhesives and glues, which normally require the mixing of raw materials in a heated vessel for a period of time to form a quantity of end product.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Other important examples are the production of food, beverages and medicine.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Batch processes are generally used to produce a relatively low to intermediate quantity of product per year (a few pounds to millions of pounds).
[src:scada-historian/process-control] A continuous physical system is represented through variables that are smooth and uninterrupted in time.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] The control of the water temperature in a heating jacket, for example, is an example of continuous process control.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Some important continuous processes are the production of fuels, chemicals and plastics.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Continuous processes in manufacturing are used to produce very large quantities of product per year (millions to billions of pounds).
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Such controls use feedback such as in the PID controller A PID Controller includes proportional, integrating, and derivative controller functions.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Applications having elements of batch and continuous process control are often called hybrid applications.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] The fundamental building block of any industrial control system is the control loop, which controls just one process variable.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] An example is shown in the accompanying diagram, where the flow rate in a pipe is controlled by a PID controller, assisted by what is effectively a cascaded loop in the form of a valve servo-controller to ensure correct valve positioning.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Some large systems may have several hundreds or thousands of control loops.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] In complex processes the loops are interactive, so that the operation of one loop may affect the operation of another.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] The system diagram for representing control loops is a Piping and instrumentation diagram.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Commonly used control systems include programmable logic controller (PLC), Distributed Control System (DCS) or SCADA.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] If a control valve were used to hold level in a tank, the level controller would compare the equivalent reading of a level sensor to the level setpoint and determine whether more or less valve opening was necessary to keep the level constant.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] A cascaded flow controller could then calculate the change in the valve position.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] The economic nature of many products manufactured in batch and continuous processes require highly efficient operation due to thin margins.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] The competing factor in process control is that products must meet certain specifications in order to be satisfactory.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] These specifications can come in two forms: a minimum and maximum for a property of the material or product, or a range within which the property must be.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] All loops are susceptible to disturbances and therefore a buffer must be used on process set points to ensure disturbances do not cause the material or product to go out of specifications.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] This buffer comes at an economic cost (i.e. additional processing, maintaining elevated or depressed process conditions, etc.).
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Process efficiency can be enhanced by reducing the margins necessary to ensure product specifications are met.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] This can be done by improving the control of the process to minimize the effect of disturbances on the process.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] The efficiency is improved in a two step method of narrowing the variance and shifting the target.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Margins can be narrowed through various process upgrades (i.e. equipment upgrades, enhanced control methods, etc.).
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Once margins are narrowed, an economic analysis can be done on the process to determine how the set point target is to be shifted.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Less conservative process set points lead to increased economic efficiency.
[src:scada-historian/process-control] Effective process control strategies increase the competitive advantage of manufacturers who employ them.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The operator interfaces, which enable monitoring and the issuing of process commands, such as controller setpoint changes, are handled through the SCADA computer system.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The subordinated operations, e.g. the real-time control logic or controller calculations, are performed by networked modules connected to the field sensors and actuators.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The SCADA concept was developed to be a universal means of remote-access to a variety of local control modules, which could be from different manufacturers and allowing access through standard automation protocols.
[src:scada-historian/scada] In practice, large SCADA systems have grown to become similar to DCSs in function, while using multiple means of interfacing with the plant.
[src:scada-historian/scada] They can control large-scale processes spanning multiple sites, and work over large distances.
[src:scada-historian/scada] It is one of the most commonly used types of industrial control systems.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The key attribute of a SCADA system is its ability to perform a supervisory operation over a variety of other proprietary devices.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Level 1 contains the programmable logic controllers (PLCs) or remote terminal units (RTUs).
[src:scada-historian/scada] Level 2 contains the SCADA to readings and equipment status reports that are communicated to level 2 SCADA as required.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Data is then compiled and formatted in such a way that a control room operator using the human-machine interface (HMI) can make supervisory decisions to adjust or override normal RTU (PLC) controls.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Data may also be fed to a historian, often built on a commodity database management system, to allow trending and other analytical auditing.
[src:scada-historian/scada] SCADA systems typically use a *tag database*, which contains data elements called *tags* or *points*, which relate to specific instrumentation or actuators within the process system.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Data is accumulated against these unique process control equipment tag references.
[src:scada-historian/scada] This is the core of the SCADA system, gathering data on the process and sending control commands to the field connected devices.
[src:scada-historian/scada] It refers to the computer and software responsible for communicating with the field connection controllers, which are RTUs and PLCs, and includes the HMI software running on operator workstations.
[src:scada-historian/scada] In smaller SCADA systems, the supervisory computer may be composed of a single PC, in which case the HMI is a part of this computer.
[src:scada-historian/scada] In larger SCADA systems, the master station may include several HMIs hosted on client computers, multiple servers for data acquisition, distributed software applications, and disaster recovery sites.
[src:scada-historian/scada] formation providing continuous control and monitoring in the event of a server malfunction or breakdown.
[src:scada-historian/scada] connect to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory computer system.
[src:scada-historian/scada] system, using radio, GSM or satellite for communications, and being ruggedised to survive from -20C to +70C or even -40C to +85C without external heating or cooling equipment.
[src:scada-historian/scada] PLCs are connected to sensors and actuators in the process, and are networked to the supervisory system.
[src:scada-historian/scada] In factory automation, PLCs typically have a high speed connection to the SCADA system.
[src:scada-historian/scada] In remote applications, such as a large water treatment plant, PLCs may connect directly to SCADA over a wireless link, or more commonly, utilise an RTU for the communications management.
[src:scada-historian/scada] For economical reasons, PLCs are often used for remote sites where there is a large I/O count, rather than utilising an RTU alone.
[src:scada-historian/scada] This connects the supervisory computer system to the RTUs and PLCs, and may use industry standard or manufacturer proprietary protocols.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Both RTUs and PLCs operate autonomously on the near-real time control of the process, using the last command given from the supervisory system.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Failure of the communications network does not necessarily stop the plant process controls, and on resumption of communications, the operator can continue with monitoring and control.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Some critical systems will have dual redundant data highways, often cabled via diverse routes.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The HMI is the operator window of the supervisory system.
[src:scada-historian/scada] It presents plant information to the operating personnel graphically in the form of mimic diagrams, which are a schematic representation of the plant being controlled, and alarm and event logging pages.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The HMI is linked to the SCADA supervisory computer to provide live data to drive the mimic diagrams, alarm displays and trending graphs.
[src:scada-historian/scada] In many installations the HMI is the graphical user interface for the operator, collects all data from external devices, creates reports, performs alarming, sends notifications, etc.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Mimic diagrams consist of line graphics and schematic symbols to represent process elements, or may consist of digital photographs of the process equipment overlain with animated symbols.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Supervisory operation of the plant is by means of the HMI, with operators issuing commands using mouse pointers, keyboards and touch screens.
[src:scada-historian/scada] For example, a symbol of a pump can show the operator that the pump is running, and a flow meter symbol can show how much fluid it is pumping through the pipe.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The operator can switch the pump off from the mimic by a mouse click or screen touch.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The HMI will show the flow rate of the fluid in the pipe decrease in real time.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The HMI package for a SCADA system typically includes a drawing program that the operators or system maintenance personnel use to change the way these points are represented in the interface.
[src:scada-historian/scada] These representations can be as simple as an on-screen traffic light, which represents the state of an actual traffic light in the field, or as complex as a multi-projector display representing the position of all of the elevators in a skyscraper or all of the trains on a railway.
[src:scada-historian/scada] is a software service within the HMI which accumulates time-stamped data, events, and alarms in a database which can be queried or used to populate graphic trends in the HMI.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The historian is a client that requests data from a data acquisition server.
[src:scada-historian/scada] An important part of most SCADA implementations is alarm handling.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The system monitors whether certain alarm conditions are satisfied, to determine when an alarm event has occurred.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Once an alarm event has been detected, one or more actions are taken (such as the activation of one or more alarm indicators, and perhaps the generation of email or text messages so that management or remote SCADA operators are informed).
[src:scada-historian/scada] In many cases, a SCADA operator may have to acknowledge the alarm event; this may deactivate some alarm indicators, whereas other indicators remain active until the alarm conditions are cleared.
[src:scada-historian/scada] "Smart" RTUs, or standard PLCs, are capable of autonomously executing simple logic processes without involving the supervisory computer.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Unlike a procedural language like C or FORTRAN, IEC 61131-3 has minimal training requirements by virtue of resembling historic physical control arrays.
[src:scada-historian/scada] This allows SCADA system engineers to perform both the design and implementation of a program to be executed on an RTU or PLC.
[src:scada-historian/scada] A programmable automation controller (PAC) is a compact controller that combines the features and capabilities of a PC-based control system with that of a typical PLC.
[src:scada-historian/scada] PACs are deployed in SCADA systems to provide RTU and PLC functions.
[src:scada-historian/scada] In many electrical substation SCADA applications, "distributed RTUs" use information processors or station computers to communicate with digital protective relays, PACs, and other devices for I/O, and communicate with the SCADA master in lieu of a traditional RTU.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Since about 1998, virtually all major PLC manufacturers have offered integrated HMI/SCADA systems, many of them using open and non-proprietary communications protocols.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The Remote Terminal Unit (RTU) connects to physical equipment.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Typically, an RTU converts the electrical signals from the equipment to digital values.
[src:scada-historian/scada] By converting and sending these electrical signals out to equipment the RTU can control equipment.
[src:scada-historian/scada] SCADA systems have traditionally used combinations of radio and direct wired connections, although SONET/SDH is also frequently used for large systems such as railways and power stations.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The remote management or monitoring function of a SCADA system is often referred to as telemetry.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Some users want SCADA data to travel over their pre-established corporate networks or to share the network with other applications.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The legacy of the early low-bandwidth protocols remains, though.
[src:scada-historian/scada] SCADA protocols are designed to be very compact.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Many are designed to send information only when the master station polls the RTU.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Typical legacy SCADA protocols include Modbus RTU, RP-570, Profibus and Conitel.
[src:scada-historian/scada] These communication protocols, with the exception of Modbus (Modbus has been made open by Schneider Electric), are all SCADA-vendor specific but are widely adopted and used.
[src:scada-historian/scada] These communication protocols are standardized and recognized by all major SCADA vendors.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Many of these protocols now contain extensions to operate over TCP/IP.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Although the use of conventional networking specifications, such as TCP/IP, blurs the line between traditional and industrial networking, they each fulfill fundamentally differing requirements.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Network simulation can be used in conjunction with SCADA simulators to perform various 'what-if' analyses.
[src:scada-historian/scada] With increasing security demands (such as North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC) and critical infrastructure protection (CIP) in the US), there is increasing use of satellite-based communication.
[src:scada-historian/scada] This has the key advantages that the infrastructure can be self-contained (not using circuits from the public telephone system), can have built-in encryption, and can be engineered to the availability and reliability required by the SCADA system operator.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Earlier experiences using consumer-grade VSAT were poor.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Modern carrier-class systems provide the quality of service required for SCADA.
[src:scada-historian/scada] RTUs and other automatic controller devices were developed before the advent of industry wide standards for interoperability.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The result is that developers and their management created a multitude of control protocols.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Among the larger vendors, there was also the incentive to create their own protocol to "lock in" their customer base.
[src:scada-historian/scada] A list of automation protocols is compiled here.
[src:scada-historian/scada] An example of efforts by vendor groups to standardize automation protocols is the OPC-UA (formerly "OLE for process control" now Open Platform Communications Unified Architecture).
[src:scada-historian/scada] Early SCADA system computing was done by large minicomputers.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Common network services did not exist at the time SCADA was developed.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Thus SCADA systems were independent systems with no connectivity to other systems.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The communication protocols used were strictly proprietary at that time.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The first-generation SCADA system redundancy was achieved using a back-up mainframe system connected to all the remote terminal unit sites and was used in the event of failure of the primary mainframe system.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Some first generation SCADA systems were developed as "turn key" operations that ran on minicomputers such as the PDP-11 series.
[src:scada-historian/scada] SCADA information and command processing were distributed across multiple stations which were connected through a LAN.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Information was shared in near real time.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Each station was responsible for a particular task, which reduced the cost as compared to first generation SCADA.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The network protocols used were still not standardized.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Since these protocols were proprietary, very few people beyond the developers knew enough to determine how secure a SCADA installation was.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Security of the SCADA installation was usually overlooked.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Similar to a distributed architecture, any complex SCADA can be reduced to the simplest components and connected through communication protocols.
[src:scada-historian/scada] In the case of a networked design, the system may be spread across more than one LAN network called a process control network (PCN) and separated geographically.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Several distributed architecture SCADAs running in parallel, with a single supervisor and historian, could be considered a network architecture.
[src:scada-historian/scada] This allows for a more cost-effective solution in very large scale systems.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The growth of the internet has led SCADA systems to implement web technologies allowing users to view data, exchange information and control processes from anywhere in the world through standard web protocols such as HTTPS and WebSocket for live updates.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The early 2000s saw the proliferation of Web SCADA systems.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Web SCADA systems use web browsers such as Google Chrome and Mozilla Firefox as the graphical user interface (GUI) for the operators HMI.
[src:scada-historian/scada] This simplifies the client side installation and enables users to access the system from various platforms with web browsers such as servers, personal computers, laptops, tablets and mobile phones.
[src:scada-historian/scada] SCADA systems that tie together decentralized facilities such as power, oil, gas pipelines, water distribution and wastewater collection systems were designed to be open, robust, and easily operated and repaired, but not necessarily secure.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The move from proprietary technologies to more standardized and open solutions together with the increased number of connections between SCADA systems, office networks and the Internet has made them more vulnerable to types of network attacks that are relatively common in computer security.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Security researcher Jerry Brown submitted a similar advisory regarding a buffer overflow vulnerability in a Wonderware InBatchClient ActiveX control.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Both vendors made updates available prior to public vulnerability release.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Mitigation recommendations were standard patching practices and requiring VPN access for secure connectivity.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Consequently, the security of some SCADA-based systems has come into question as they are seen as potentially vulnerable to cyber attacks.
[src:scada-historian/scada] SCADA systems are used to control and monitor physical processes, examples of which are transmission of electricity, transportation of gas and oil in pipelines, water distribution, traffic lights, and other systems used as the basis of modern society.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The security of these SCADA systems is important because compromise or destruction of these systems would impact multiple areas of society far removed from the original compromise.
[src:scada-historian/scada] For example, a blackout caused by a compromised electrical SCADA system would cause financial losses to all the customers that received electricity from that source.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Legacy SCADA deployments can remain difficult to secure because control equipment is often geographically distributed, long-lived, and costly to replace or patch.
[src:scada-historian/scada] There are many threat vectors to a modern SCADA system.
[src:scada-historian/scada] One is the threat of unauthorized access to the control software, whether it is human access or changes induced intentionally or accidentally by virus infections and other software threats residing on the control host machine.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Another is the threat of packet access to the network segments hosting SCADA devices.
[src:scada-historian/scada] In many cases, the control protocol lacks any form of cryptographic security, allowing an attacker to control a SCADA device by sending commands over a network.
[src:scada-historian/scada] In many cases SCADA users have assumed that having a VPN offered sufficient protection, unaware that security can be trivially bypassed with physical access to SCADA-related network jacks and switches.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Industrial control vendors suggest approaching SCADA security like Information Security with a defense in depth strategy that leverages common IT practices.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Apart from that, research has shown that the architecture of SCADA systems has several other vulnerabilities, including direct tampering with RTUs, communication links from RTUs to the control center, and IT software and databases in the control center.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The RTUs could, for instance, be targets of deception attacks injecting false data or denial-of-service attacks.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The reliable function of SCADA systems in our modern infrastructure may be crucial to public health and safety.
[src:scada-historian/scada] As such, attacks on these systems may directly or indirectly threaten public health and safety.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Such an attack has already occurred, carried out on Maroochy Shire Council's sewage control system in Queensland, Australia.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Shortly after a contractor installed a SCADA system in January 2000, system components began to function erratically.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Pumps did not run when needed and alarms were not reported.
[src:scada-historian/scada] More critically, sewage flooded a nearby park and contaminated an open surface-water drainage ditch and flowed 500 meters to a tidal canal.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The SCADA system was directing sewage valves to open when the design protocol should have kept them closed.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Initially this was believed to be a system bug.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Monitoring of the system logs revealed the malfunctions were the result of cyber attacks.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Investigators reported 46 separate instances of malicious outside interference before the culprit was identified.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The attacks were made by a disgruntled ex-employee of the company that had installed the SCADA system.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The ex-employee was hoping to be hired by the utility full-time to maintain the system.
[src:scada-historian/scada] In April 2008, the *Commission to Assess the Threat to the United States from Electromagnetic Pulse (EMP) Attack* issued a *Critical Infrastructures Report* document which discussed the extreme vulnerability of SCADA systems to an electromagnetic pulse (EMP) event.
[src:scada-historian/scada] After testing and analysis, the commission concluded: "SCADA systems are vulnerable to EMP insult.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The large numbers and widespread reliance on such systems by all of the Nation’s critical infrastructures represent a systemic threat to their continued operation following an EMP event.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Many vendors of SCADA and control products have begun to address the risks posed by unauthorized access by developing lines of specialized industrial firewall and VPN solutions for TCP/IP-based SCADA networks as well as external SCADA monitoring and recording equipment.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The International Society of Automation (ISA) started formalizing SCADA security requirements in 2007 with a working group, WG4.
[src:scada-historian/scada] WG4 "deals specifically with unique technical requirements, measurements, and other features required to evaluate and assure security resilience and performance of industrial automation and control systems devices".
[src:scada-historian/scada] The increased interest in SCADA vulnerabilities has resulted in vulnerability researchers discovering vulnerabilities in commercial SCADA software and more general offensive SCADA techniques presented to the general security community.
[src:scada-historian/scada] In June 2010, anti-virus security company VirusBlokAda reported the first detection of malware that attacks SCADA systems (Siemens' WinCC/PCS 7 systems) running on Windows operating systems.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The malware is called Stuxnet and uses four zero-day attacks to install a rootkit which in turn logs into the SCADA's database and steals design and control files.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The malware is also capable of changing the control system and hiding those changes.
[src:scada-historian/scada] The malware was found on 14 systems, the majority of which were located in Iran.
[src:scada-historian/scada] In October 2013 *National Geographic* released a docudrama titled *American Blackout* which dealt with an imagined large-scale cyber attack on SCADA and the United States' electrical grid.
[src:scada-historian/scada] Both large and small systems can be built using the SCADA concept.
[src:scada-historian/scada] These systems can range from just tens to thousands of control loops, depending on the application.
[src:scada-historian/scada] However, SCADA systems may have security vulnerabilities, so the systems should be evaluated to identify risks and solutions implemented to mitigate those risks.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] A **time series database** is a software system that is optimized for storing and serving time series through associated pairs of time(s) and value(s).
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] In some fields, *time series* may be called profiles, curves, traces or trends.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] Several early time series databases are associated with industrial applications which could efficiently store measured values from sensory equipment (also referred to as data historians), but now are used in support of a much wider range of applications.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] In many cases, the repositories of time-series data will utilize compression algorithms to manage the data efficiently.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] Although it is possible to store time-series data in many different database types, the design of these systems with time as a key index is distinctly different from relational databases which reduce discrete relationships through referential models.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] Time series datasets are relatively large and uniform compared to other datasets―usually being composed of a timestamp and associated data.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] Time series datasets can also have fewer relationships between data entries in different tables and don't require indefinite storage of entries.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] The unique properties of time series datasets mean that time series databases can provide significant improvements in storage space and performance over general purpose databases.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] For instance, due to the uniformity of time series data, specialized compression algorithms can provide improvements over regular compression algorithms designed to work on less uniform data.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] Time series databases can also be configured to regularly delete (or downsample) old data, unlike regular databases which are designed to store data indefinitely.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] Special database indices can also provide boosts in query performance.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] Time series databases are commonly designed for append-heavy workloads, where large numbers of measurements or events are continuously written together with timestamps.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] Specialized time series management systems have been developed for data from monitoring, automation, the Internet of Things, and cyber-physical systems, where data may be produced at high velocity and in large volumes.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] Common design goals include high-throughput data ingestion, low-latency queries over time ranges, efficient compression, and support for aggregation or downsampling over time windows.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] Many systems also organize data by tags, devices, sensors, or other metadata, so that users can retrieve measurements by both time range and source.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] Time series databases are used in application areas where data is collected continuously over time.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] Examples include industrial monitoring, operational historians, infrastructure and application monitoring, Internet of Things sensor data, energy systems, financial market data, and scientific measurements.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] In monitoring applications, time series database systems may need to process large amounts of sensor or metric data in real time, execute continuous queries, and support analytical tasks such as data exploration, anomaly detection, predictive modeling, trend analysis, and missing-value recovery.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] Time series databases are often used as storage and query systems for downstream analytical tasks, including forecasting, anomaly detection, imputation, and pattern matching.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] Some systems also integrate analytical or machine-learning functions closer to the database layer, allowing users to invoke forecasting or anomaly detection through database query interfaces such as SQL.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] Recent research in time series analysis has also explored large pre-trained models for tasks such as forecasting, imputation, and anomaly detection.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] These models are usually discussed as analytical methods for time series data rather than as defining features of time series databases.
[src:scada-historian/time-series-database] The following database systems have functionality optimized for handling time series data.
